    public const string TerminologyEn =
        "Scholarships are described with words that mean different things in different countries — and confusing them costs students money and time. Here is the practical glossary the platform uses. " +
        "A fully funded scholarship covers tuition, accommodation, a monthly stipend, health insurance and usually a one-time travel allowance. The student is expected to cover only minor personal expenses. A partially funded scholarship covers a defined subset — most commonly a tuition waiver of 30%, 50% or 80% — leaving the student to pay the rest plus living costs. " +
        "A tuition waiver reduces or zeroes the published tuition fee but does not include a stipend. A merit scholarship is awarded on academic or extracurricular merit; a need-based scholarship is awarded on demonstrated financial need; a hybrid programme uses both. A bursary, in many countries, is a smaller one-off grant — usually need-based. A fellowship typically refers to graduate-level funding with a research or teaching component, often including a stipend higher than a normal scholarship. " +
        "A grant differs from a scholarship in that it is rarely competitive in the same way: it is awarded once eligibility is met, and is more common for specific projects, research costs or living-cost support. A loan is repayable, even if subsidised — never confuse a loan with a scholarship. A government-sponsored scholarship is funded by the destination country or your home country and usually carries a service obligation: a number of years working in your home country after graduation. " +
        "When you see \"financial aid package\" in an offer letter, read it carefully: the package can stack a partial scholarship, a departmental award, a work-study allowance and a small grant. Add them up before deciding the offer is or is not affordable.";

