    public const string SopWritingEn =
        "A statement of purpose is the single piece of writing that selection panels read most carefully. The strongest statements share the same structure. " +
        "Open with a specific moment, not a general claim. \"I have always loved learning\" is forgettable. \"In my second year, I rebuilt our family bakery's inventory system on weekends — that is when I knew I wanted to study supply chain analytics\" is a paragraph the reviewer remembers. " +
        "After the opening, devote one paragraph to academic preparation: what you studied, why it matters, and one or two concrete achievements. Resist the temptation to list every honour. Pick the two most relevant to the programme you are applying to and explain what they taught you. " +
        "The next paragraph belongs to why this programme, at this institution. Generic praise of a university is a wasted paragraph. Specific reasons — a particular professor's research, a course you read about that does not exist elsewhere, an alumni network in your home country — make the reviewer believe you have done your homework. " +
        "Reserve one paragraph for the future. What will you do during the programme? What problems will you work on? What do you intend to do in the five years afterwards? Reviewers are funding a trajectory, not a CV — show them where their investment leads. " +
        "Close briefly and concretely. Avoid restating the opening. End with a forward-looking sentence that connects your goals to the scholarship's mission. " +
        "Practical limits: 700 to 900 words for most programmes; 500 words if the prompt specifies; never exceed the word limit. Read it aloud at least once. Ask one reader inside your field and one outside it to read and comment.";

