    public const string RecommendationFaqEn =
        "Recommendation letters are usually the deciding factor between two candidates with similar academic records. They are also the most under-managed part of the application — students assume \"my professor will write whatever they want\" and accept whatever they get. The strongest applicants manage the letter actively. " +
        "Who to ask. Pick people who have observed you doing the thing the scholarship is about. A junior lecturer who saw you lead a class project writes a more credible letter than a famous professor who saw you in a 200-person lecture. Two strong specific letters are better than three vague generic ones. " +
        "When to ask. Six weeks before the earliest deadline is the minimum. Reminder of three weeks, then ten days, then 72 hours is reasonable. Anything closer than three weeks risks a hastily written letter. " +
        "What to send with the request. A short brief makes the writer's job easy: which scholarship, what the deadline is, why you are applying, your CV, a draft of your statement of purpose, and two or three points you hope the letter could touch on — a specific project, a moment when you solved a problem, an interaction the writer remembers. Many writers will lift sentences directly from your brief. That is fine. " +
        "Format and submission. Most scholarships now require the letter to be submitted directly by the writer, often through a secure link. Send your writer the link the moment it is generated. Some scholarships still accept letters on letterhead emailed to a committee inbox — confirm the exact requirement before relying on memory. " +
        "After submission. Thank your writer in writing. When you get an outcome — accepted, rejected, deferred — tell them. Writers remember candidates who close the loop, and they write better letters next time.";

