    public const string VisaUkEn =
        "The UK Student visa (formerly Tier 4) is required for non-UK nationals studying any course longer than six months. The current rules — accurate at the time of writing — are described below. Always cross-check with the official UKVI site and your university's international office before relying on any single source. " +
        "Eligibility. You need an unconditional offer (a Confirmation of Acceptance for Studies, CAS) from a licensed sponsor, demonstrated English proficiency at the required level, evidence of sufficient funds to cover your first year of tuition plus prescribed living costs (around £1,334 per month inside London and £1,023 outside London), and a clean criminal record. " +
        "The 28-day rule. The funds you show must have been in your named account (or your parent's named account, with a signed declaration) for at least 28 consecutive days before you apply. The closing balance of that period must meet the threshold. Large deposits in the last days look like borrowed funds and are a common rejection reason. " +
        "Application process. The application is submitted online via gov.uk, with biometric data captured at a Visa Application Centre. You will need a tuberculosis certificate if you come from a listed country, an Academic Technology Approval Scheme (ATAS) clearance for some STEM courses, and the immigration health surcharge paid up front (£776 per year for students at the time of writing). " +
        "Processing time and outcome. Decisions inside the published service standard take three weeks for standard applications; priority and super priority services exist for an extra fee. Once approved, you receive a vignette in your passport valid for 90 days, during which you must collect a Biometric Residence Permit (BRP) from a post office in the UK within 10 days of arrival.";

