    public const string VisaUsEn =
        "The F-1 student visa is the main route for academic study in the United States. The process has two distinct phases — first an I-20 from your university, then the consular interview at a US embassy or consulate. " +
        "Step 1: the I-20. After you accept your offer, your university's international student office issues an I-20 — a form that proves your enrolment and the cost of the programme. You must pay the SEVIS I-901 fee (currently $350) before applying for the visa. Keep the SEVIS payment receipt; the consular officer will ask. " +
        "Step 2: the DS-160 and DS-160 confirmation. Complete the online non-immigrant visa application (DS-160). Every detail must match your passport, your I-20 and your supporting documents. Inconsistencies are a common reason for additional scrutiny. " +
        "Step 3: the interview. Schedule the interview at the US embassy or consulate in your country of residence. Bring originals of: passport, the DS-160 confirmation page, the I-20, the SEVIS fee receipt, the visa fee receipt, the admission letter, financial evidence (bank statements, scholarship award letters, sponsorship documents), and any test scores (SAT, GRE, TOEFL, IELTS) the university accepted. " +
        "Demonstrating non-immigrant intent. F-1 visas are non-immigrant: you must convince the officer you plan to return home after your studies. Family ties, property, future job prospects in your home country, and a clear post-graduation plan all help. \"I have no plans after graduation\" is the answer that most often causes a refusal under section 214(b). " +
        "After approval. Visa-stamped passports are usually returned by courier within one to two weeks. F-1 students can enter the US up to 30 days before the programme start date listed on the I-20.";

