    public const string IeltsPrepEn =
        "Most English-taught Master's programmes require IELTS 6.5 overall, with 6.0 in each section. Top programmes require 7.0 overall with 6.5 in each section. Doctoral programmes commonly require 7.0 or higher. Decide your target band before you book the test. " +
        "Format. The Academic IELTS has four sections: Listening (30 minutes plus 10 minutes transfer time, 40 questions), Reading (60 minutes, 40 questions across three passages), Writing (60 minutes for two tasks) and Speaking (11–14 minutes, three parts, face-to-face with an examiner). Listening, Reading and Writing are done on the same day; Speaking is sometimes scheduled within a week of the main test. " +
        "Eight-week preparation plan. Weeks 1–2: take a baseline mock, identify your weakest section, build a vocabulary set of 250 high-frequency academic words. Weeks 3–5: focused drills on your weakest section, with one full timed mock per week. Weeks 6–7: two full timed mocks per week, with Writing and Speaking marked against the official band descriptors. Week 8: one light mock, rest, identity documents and test centre route confirmed. " +
        "Strategies by section. Listening: predict question types from the format and write quick notes — half of lost marks are misspellings, not mishearings. Reading: skim questions first, then scan the passage; manage time by spending 20 minutes per passage. Writing Task 2 carries more weight than Task 1 — spend 40 minutes there, 20 on Task 1. Speaking: extend answers in Part 1 (two or three sentences), take a breath before Part 3 to organise your point. " +
        "Score validity. IELTS scores are valid for two years from the test date — schedule the test so the results stay valid through the start of your programme.";

