    public const string ToeflPrepEn =
        "Most US universities accept TOEFL iBT as proof of English. The typical Master's requirement is 90 with no section below 22; competitive programmes require 100 with no section below 25. Doctoral programmes commonly require 100 or higher. " +
        "Format. The TOEFL iBT is fully digital, around three hours: Reading (35 minutes, two passages of 10 questions each), Listening (36 minutes, six lectures or conversations), Speaking (16 minutes, four tasks), Writing (29 minutes, two tasks — an integrated task that combines reading, listening and writing, and an academic discussion task). All sections are scored on 0–30, totalling 0–120. " +
        "A 30-day study plan. Days 1–5: baseline mock and a study calendar. Days 6–15: drill the weakest section daily, integrate the others on alternating days. Days 16–25: mix all four sections daily; do one full timed mock at the midpoint. Days 26–28: three full timed mocks on consecutive days, score honestly, list common errors. Days 29–30: no new content, rest, prepare test centre logistics. " +
        "Tactics by section. Reading: skim the passage first, then read questions; do not memorise vocabulary lists — read in context. Listening: take structured notes (main idea, examples, attitude markers); the TOEFL rewards understanding of organisation, not just facts. Speaking: practice the integrated tasks aloud until you can summarise a reading and lecture in 60 seconds. Writing: the integrated task carries equal weight; practise paraphrasing the reading and the lecture into your own academic English. " +
        "Score validity. TOEFL iBT scores are valid for two years from the test date.";

